9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.118d0ecd-b79f-4309-8a11-4f9ac6b27529.prompt=Database Name\: 9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.23fac955-332f-40ea-a542-34cc6a224771.description=
This operation writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file, append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Inputs\:
    source -  Full path to file. If the file does not exist it is created first.
    contents - The content that should be written to the file. This input field can contain more lines, separated by a delimiter. If it contains the new line character (\n or \r\n), but this is not the delimiter, this character will be escaped and written to file.  
Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
    delimiter - Specifies the newline delimiter that is used to split the "contents" input field into separate lines that will be further written to the given file.
Examples\: \n, \r\n, etc
    characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. 
Default\: UTF-8. 
Valid values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.
    overwrite - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. 
Default\: true. 
Valid values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "success" confirmation message if the operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - It has the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and 1 otherwise.
    exception - This contains an exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - File/directory was written successfully.
    failure - Unable to write to file/directory, empty contents or source.

Examples\:
1. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Windows\:
    source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,

2. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Linux\:
    source\: /root/example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,
9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.40342b7a-b1c3-4fab-8e33-f43e3951136a.description=
Runs a SQL SELECT query.
Returns the complete result like the following\:
a1b2

Inputs\:
    DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of db server.
    DbType - The type of database to connect to. 
Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2 and Custom.
Default value\: Oracle
    Username - The username to use when connecting to the server.
    Password -  The password to use when connecting to the server.
    instance - The name instance of MSSQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
    DbPort - The port to connect to.
Default values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000.
    Database - The name of the database.
    authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). 
Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL)
Default value\: sql
    dbClass - The classname of the JDBC driver to use.
    dbURL - The url required to load up the driver and make your connection.
    Command - The command to execute.
    colDelimiter - The delimiter to use between columns in resulting table.
Default value\: comma (,)
    rowDelimiter - The delimiter to use between rows in resulting table.
Default value\: \n
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution.
Default value\: 0 
    databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. Form more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description.
Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Return the list of all the data returned by the query. It is delimited by colDelimiter and rowDelimiter. 

Responses\:
    success - The command was executed successfully. 
    failure - Failed to execute the command. 

Note\: 
    SQL statement other than SELECT statement (like INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE) is not supported. In case statements other than SELECT are executed then the operation will fail but the statements might get partially or fully executed in the database.
    Check the JDBC  folder description for details on how to load database connectors.
9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.4fd05396-bc63-4eb5-b72e-fbbf5dffd576.transition.description=FECHA PROCESO \= ${fecha_proceso} 9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.520c871b-d3cb-4567-8347-97eab5e5cfd3.transition.description=${nombre_query} 9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.67108398-b920-4b80-8f20-dfb135e73561.description=
Performs a mathematical operation on two numbers

Inputs\:
operator - The operation to perform (+, -, *, /, <, >, <\=, >\=, \=\=, \!\=).
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
The result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully. If a boolean operation, it evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.
9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.69ff90b6-cee2-47b4-b095-ae6a56bd3143.description=
Uses Secure FTP (SFTP) to send a file on a RAS to a remote host.  

Inputs\:
host - IP address/host name.
port - The port to connect to on host.
username - Remote username.
password - Password to authenticate. If using a private key file this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
privateKey - Absolute path for private key file for public/private key authentication.
localFile - The path to the file on the RAS to be copied remotely using SFTP.
remoteLocation - The remote location where the file is to be placed.
characterSet - The name of the control encoding to use. Examples\: UTF-8, EUC-JP, SJIS.  Default is UTF-8.
closeSession - Close the SSH session at completion of operation?  Default value is true.  If false the SSH session can be reused by other SFTP commands in the same flow.  Valid values\: true, false.

Responses\:
success - Command completed successfully.
failure - Command failed.

Result\:
Local file will be copied to Remote system.
9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.746e96c3-f64a-4604-a9c9-95447618ff5d.description=
Runs multiple Shell commands by creating a SSH shell and checking output against regular expressions.

Inputs\:
    host - The hostname/IP address of the target machine.
    port - The port number for SSH protocol.
Default value\: 22
    username - Name of the account on the target machine.
    password - The password for the username. When using a private key file or a private key string, this input will be used as the passphrase for the file or string. For security reasons it is recommend to provide this input and protect the private key when using the 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs.
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the remote machine.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default\: 8080. Valid values\: -1 and numbers greater than 0.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    privateKeyFile - Path to private key file (OpenSSH type) on the machine where is the worker. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    privateKeyData – A string representing the private key (OpenSSH type) used for authenticating the user. This string is usually the content of a private key file. The 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs are mutually exclusive. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    knownHostsPolicy - The policy used for managing known_hosts file. We recommend to use a "strict" policy so as to verify the host key against a local file containing known, trustworthy machines. If you choose "allow" or "add" policy then you will connect to the server without any verification. If there is a Man-In-The-Middle attack then you will be connected to a fake server and the SSH commands that you send will go through that fake server. 
Valid values\:  
allow\=It will permit the connection to any hosts. 
strict\=It will permit the connection only to the hosts specified in known_hosts file. 
add\=It will permit the connection to any hosts, if the host is not in the known_hosts file it will be added. 
Default value\: strict
    allowedCiphers - A comma separated list of ciphers that will be used in the client-server handshake mechanism when the connection is created. Check the notes section for security concerns regarding your choice of ciphers. The default value will be used even if the input is not added to the operation.
Default value\: aes128-ctr,aes128-cbc,3des-ctr,3des-cbc,blowfish-cbc,aes192-ctr,aes192-cbc,aes256-ctr,aes256-cbc
    command - The commands to execute. This should be made up of 'send ' and 'expect ' statements separated by newlineCharacters.
    characterSet - The characterSet name for input stream encoding from the target machine.
Examples\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8
Default value\: UTF-8
    newlineCharacters - The character sequence to send as the enter key being pressed after each 'send' statement as the send expect script is processed in the command input. Either '\r\n' '\n' '\r' or a comma delimited list of ASCII escape sequences.
    timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete.
Default value\: 90000
    connectTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the connection to be made.
Default value\: 10000
    sessionId - Identifier of a shared SSH shell session created by SSH Shell Logon. Instead of creating a new SSH shell session this one will be used if specified.

Results\:
    returnResult - The primary output.
    STDOUT - The standard output of the command(s).
    visualized - The output of the command in XML format.
    TimedOut - Is set to "true" if the value set in the "timeout" input has elapsed and the command timed out.

Responses\:
    success - The operation was executed successfully.
    failure - The connection could not be established or the commands are invalid for this operation (not for target machine's shell).

Notes\:
1. The following commands are supported\:
1.1. Send a Shell command.
    send 
Examples\: send ls
1.2. Send a char given by ASCII code.
    sendChar 
Examples\: sendChar 32
1.3. Match the entire previous command output against the regex.
    expect 
Examples\: expect (.*?)Desktop(.*)
1.4. The entire previous command output ends with the given text.
    expectEndsWith 
1.5. Match the last line from the previous command output against the regex.
    expectLastLine 
1.6. Fail on the success of the expect command\: expect, expectEndsWith or expectLastLine.
    errorOn 
1.7. If the expect command is successful then the operation will always execute the send command.
    always 
    on 
Examples\: 
Single line output\: always sendChar 121
                           on expect (.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
Multiple line output example 1\: always sendChar 121
                             	 on expect (?s)(.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
Multiple line output example 2\: always sendChar 121
                             	 on expectLastLine (.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
1.8. Use a different timeout for this send command\: send, sendChar.
    wait  
1.9. Use a different timeout for this expect command\: expect, expectEndsWith or expectLastLine.
    wait  
2. Hidden inputs\:
    knownHostsPath -  Specifies the path to the known_hots file on the running server.
Default value\: /.ssh/known_hosts
Examples\: /home/admin/.ssh/known_hosts
    readTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for reading and then matching the output with the regex from expect command.
Default value\: 20000
3. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service.
4. The operation supports connections through HTTP proxy with username and password authentication.
5. For security reasons, HPE does not recommend the use of outdated or vulnerable ciphers. Therefore "arcfour" cihpers should be avoided because they do not provide confidentiality for data in transit and using them can lead to information leakage.
Arcfour is vulnerable to the following attacks\: Fluhrer, Mantin and Shamir attack, Klein's attack, Royal Holloway attack, Bar-mitzvah attack and NOMORE attack.

Escribe archivo .csv con los datos extraídos 9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.8f67c55f-a8e3-4d83-99eb-ff7f551369cf.prompt=HostName\: 9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.b42b8830-0fe2-497f-8c16-d071d7e6ca7f.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
9a34a421-01ae-4c03-9edf-db744b18b307.cde9b4cb-81f7-4eb8-9ce1-9a2c6005e941.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-yyyy HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2

F	Day of week in month			Number		2

u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0

K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12

s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00

Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry

Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
